    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-07T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-07T20:00:00-05:00" n="4"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d4">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/1369: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-08T10:00:00+09:00"
                            >January 8, 1935—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 8—4:32 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3. The Soviet Ambassador<note n="8" xml:id="d4fn8">Constantin Yurenev.</note>
                    told me last night that the press reports of an early settlement of the sale of
                    the Chinese Eastern Railway are unfounded and have been announced from Japanese
                    sources merely to strengthen Hirota’s<note n="9" xml:id="d4fn9">Koki Hirota,
                        Japanese Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> position in the forthcoming
                    sessions of the Diet. Some slight advance has been made in the negotiations but
                    the question of guarantees of payment is still unsettled.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
